After the birdsong, though, for a moment, silence – the quietest you can imagine – descended. And then, from the surrounding city, the sound of music began to fill the air. In the distance, it was just the murmur of a voice, but it was clear it was the morning sermon of a church somewhere.

Dette er viktig for kommunene.

The municipality is responsible for collecting data on the amount of noise that can be found from traffic. This means noise from all types of vehicles on the road and road construction works. The municipality is also responsible for assessing how the road and traffic noise impacts residents. The municipality also needs to assess whether the impact on residents is acceptable or not. If this is not the case, the municipality must act on the issue to get it as close to acceptable as possible.

The municipality is ultimately responsible for making sure that rules and regulations related to noise are complied with. This is not necessarily always the responsibility of the municipality, such as when the roads are operated by other authorities than the county council. Often then it will be the county road authority the is responsible for monitoring and reporting.

The municipality is usually responsible for roads in the immediate city area. The county administrative board is usually responsible for roads outside of the municipalities.

The Helle Viking Belt is a handcrafted belt that combines design, functionality and craftsmanship. It is made of supple cow leather that is vegetable tanned, and the belt itself can be adjusted by the slide buckle design. It can be used as a belt or as a fashionable wristband. The Viking Belt is based on findings from late Viking grave sites in Denmark. All Viking belts were cut out from one piece of leather and were originally used more for ornamental and prestige reasons, as a status symbol, then a functional garment to hold up your pants. The Viking belt is designed to be worn with a tunic or tights, as that’s what was worn during the Viking era.

If you know a little about Norse mythology, you know Yggdrasil’s roots are guarded by NIðhöggr (Nið) and Na̱uðr (Noaðr), the serpent and the eagle.

05.07.2019

In Norway we are preparing a national plan for 2050 and measures to be implemented to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

The Norwegian Environment Agency’s (NEA) role in the climate and energy work is to provide the public authorities concerned with information and analyses that form the basis for decisions and to perform independent monitoring of the measures introduced to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
